<ServicePageLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  headings={headings}
  faqItems={faqItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  heroImageUrl="/images/pet-hospice-hero.jpg"
  heroImageAlt="An elderly dog receiving gentle affection from their owner"
>
  <h2 id="what-is-pet-hospice">What is Pet Hospice?</h2>
  <p>Veterinary hospice, also known as palliative care, is a specialized approach to caring for a pet with a terminal illness or advanced age. Just like in human medicine, when a cure is no longer achievable, the focus shifts to providing comfort, relieving pain, and maintaining the highest possible quality of life for whatever time remains.</p>

  <h2 id="palliative-care-focus">The Focus of Palliative Care</h2>
  <p>Hospice care is highly individualized based on the pet's specific needs and the family's capabilities. Key components often include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pain Management:</strong> Utilizing medications and therapies to keep your pet comfortable.</li>
    <li><strong>Nutritional Support:</strong> Adjusting diet, offering appetizing foods, or managing nausea to encourage eating.</li>
    <li><strong>Hydration:</strong> Administering subcutaneous fluids at home if your pet isn't drinking enough.</li>
    <li><strong>Mobility Assistance:</strong> Using harnesses, ramps, or modifying the home environment to help your pet move safely.</li>
    <li><strong>Hygiene Care:</strong> Assisting with grooming and managing incontinence to preserve your pet's dignity.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="when-to-consider">When to Consider Hospice Care</h2>
  <p>Hospice care may be the right choice if your pet has been diagnosed with a terminal illness (like cancer or organ failure), if they are experiencing significant age-related decline, or if aggressive treatments are causing more stress than benefit. It provides a peaceful alternative to frequent, stressful clinic visits, allowing your pet to remain in the comfort of their own home.</p>

  <h2 id="supporting-the-family">Supporting the Family</h2>
  <p>Hospice isn't just about the pet; it's also about supporting the family. A hospice veterinarian will work with you to understand your goals, teach you how to administer care, help you monitor your pet's <a href="/resources/quality-of-life-scale-dog/">quality of life</a>, and provide guidance on preparing for the inevitable, including discussions about <a href="/at-home-pet-euthanasia/">euthanasia</a> when the time is right.</p>
</ServicePageLayout>
